{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646962","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646962"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:38:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:38:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18221"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18221"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0.07,0.04,0.26,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10935"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114274"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10935"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18221"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96274"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5113"},{"type":"tags","id":"10131"},{"type":"tags","id":"10203"},{"type":"tags","id":"10209"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"},{"type":"tags","id":"11271"},{"type":"tags","id":"11417"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25417"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25420"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114274"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECalcium homeostasis is a tightly regulated process involving several hormones and cellular interactions. The parathyroid hormone (PTH) and vitamin D play significant roles in maintaining calcium levels in the body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about calcium homeostasis is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["RANKL promotes the differentiation of osteoclasts leading to increased bone resorption","Vitamin D decreases intestinal absorption of calcium","Parathyroid hormone decreases renal reabsorption of calcium","Osteoprotegerin (OPG) enhances the activity of RANKL","High calcium levels stimulate the release of parathyroid hormone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERANKL promotes the differentiation of osteoclasts leading to increased bone resorption\u003C/strong\u003E. RANKL (Receptor Activator of Nuclear factor Kappa-\u03b2 Ligand) is a key factor in the formation, function, and survival of osteoclasts, which are responsible for bone resorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin D decreases intestinal absorption of calcium\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as vitamin D actually increases intestinal absorption of calcium. \u003Cstrong\u003EParathyroid hormone decreases renal reabsorption of calcium\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as parathyroid hormone increases renal reabsorption of calcium. \u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoprotegerin (OPG) enhances the activity of RANKL\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as OPG acts as a decoy receptor for RANKL, inhibiting its activity. \u003Cstrong\u003EHigh calcium levels stimulate the release of parathyroid hormone\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as high calcium levels inhibit the release of parathyroid hormone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcium homeostasis is regulated by the calcium-sensing receptor, parathyroid hormone (PTH), and vitamin D.","Low extracellular calcium levels stimulate the parathyroid glands to release PTH.","PTH acts on osteoblasts and osteocytes to increase bone resorption and release calcium into the bloodstream.","RANKL is a key mediator in the process of bone resorption, while OPG acts as a decoy receptor to inhibit RANKL.","The balance between RANKL and OPG is crucial for maintaining bone health."],"references":["Khurana I, Khurana A, Kowlgi NG. Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2019.","Clarke B. Normal bone anatomy and physiology. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2008 Nov;3 Suppl 3(Suppl 3):S131-9.","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746.","Cowan PT, Launico MV, Kahai P. Anatomy, Bones. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013.","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 80; pg. 996"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96274"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18221"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96274"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T14:35:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T14:35:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10935"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114274"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}